	<li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 parent" id="comment-8654" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-8654" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/5fb84df7269d661db6fdd71c618ca409?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://www.keptlight.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>A Cemal Ekin</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2011/photo-gallery-primer/comment-page-1/#comment-8654">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2011-06-02T22:58:27+00:00">June 2, 2011 at 10:58 pm</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>This is all very interesting, but have you not just created a &#8220;plug-in&#8221;? It uses code, it uses its own file(s), it has its own style, etc. I am not focusing on the semantics, but the notion that &#8220;WordPress has a lot of gallery functionality built in&#8221; is akin to saying &#8220;this bunch of grapes have a lot of wine in them&#8221;. I wish it really had gallery functionality built in so that we would not use plugins or develop our mini-plugins, albeit with limited functionality.</p>
</div>

	<div class="reply">
	<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/photo-gallery-primer/comment-page-1/?replytocom=8654#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-8654", "8654", "respond", "372")'>Reply to this comment</a>	</div>
