	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-otto bypostauthor even depth-2 parent" id="comment-8662" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-8662" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0994d5e2e158a24ba8017c2525d78263?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://ottodestruct.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Otto</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2011/photo-gallery-primer/comment-page-1/#comment-8662">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2011-06-03T05:37:43+00:00">June 3, 2011 at 5:37 am</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>No, because I&#8217;m talking about editing your THEME, which is not a plugin.</p>
<p>A plugin modifies how WordPress works. Your theme controls what WordPress displays. These are two very different things, even if they&#8217;re both made out of &#8220;code&#8221;.</p>
</div>

	<div class="reply">
	<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2011/photo-gallery-primer/comment-page-1/?replytocom=8662#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-8662", "8662", "respond", "372")'>Reply to this comment</a>	</div>
